      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become linked in such a way that the state of one instantly influences the state of the other, regardless of the distance separating them. It's often described as \"spooky action at a distance,\" a phrase coined by Einstein, who was skeptical of the idea.\n\nTo understand how this differs from classical correlation, imagine you have two coins. If you flip them and they happen to land on heads both times, that's a classical correlation; you just got lucky with the same outcome. However, in quantum entanglement, the particles don't have definite states until they are measured. If you measure one particle and find it has a spin \"up,\" the other particle will instantly be found to have a spin \"down,\" even if it's light-years away. This isn't just a pre-existing agreement between the particles like the coins; the measurement itself creates the definite state for both simultaneously.\n\nThink of it like a pair of magical dice that are always opposite, but until you roll them, they don't have a specific number. The moment you look at one, the other *becomes* its opposite instantly, which is why it defies our everyday understanding of how things",
      "source": "target",
